Pour intégrer ces projets dans ton portfolio de manière professionnelle et percutante, il faut :

  1. Structurer la présentation

    • Titre clair : "Key Projects in Epidemiology, Data Analytics, and Modeling (2020–2024)".

    • Organiser par thématique (Modeling, Analytics, SNT Support, Training) plutôt que par date brute, mais garder une frise chronologique visuelle.

    • Chaque projet doit avoir :

      • Titre précis

      • Période

      • Objectif / Contexte

      • Méthodes et outils utilisés (SAS, R, Python, EMOD, etc.)

      • Résultats / Livrables (publications, rapports, modèles, tableaux de bord, recommandations stratégiques)

      • Impact (politique de santé influencée, formation de personnel, amélioration des décisions d’intervention)

  2. Mise en forme

    • Tu peux garder la frise comme élément visuel d’introduction en haut de la page.

    • En dessous, faire une fiche par projet avec une photo/graphique, un texte court et les points clés.

    • Exemple :
      Project: Predicting the Impact of Interventions of Subnational Tailoring in Guinea
      Period: 2020–2021
      Goal: Model malaria intervention scenarios to guide national policy.
      Methods: EMOD modeling, R statistical analysis, geospatial risk mapping.
      Deliverables: Predictive models, scenario reports for NMCP Guinea.
      Impact: Informed resource allocation and targeted interventions at subnational level.

  3. Mettre en avant tes rôles et compétences

    • Toujours préciser si tu étais Lead Analyst, Principal Investigator, Data Manager, Trainer, etc.

    • Relier chaque projet à compétences clés recherchées dans tes futurs postes (ex. clinical data analysis, spatial modeling, health policy evaluation).

  4. Segment spécial “Training & Mentorship”

    • Distinguer la formation de doctorants et masters comme un bloc à part, avec témoignages ou statistiques (nombre d’étudiants, sujets encadrés, résultats).

  5. Option portfolio en ligne

    • Sur ton GitHub Pages (ousmanerabi.github.io), créer une section Projects où chaque projet aura :

      • La description

      • Des extraits de code (SAS, R)

      • Des graphiques

      • Des liens vers publications ou rapports

ChatGPT a dit :

Je vois 👍 — là tu as ajouté une collection projects dans _config.yml, mais :

  1. tes fichiers sont dans projects/ (sans _), donc ce n’est pas une collection Jekyll ;

  2. l’ajout d’une collection n’ajoute pas automatiquement un onglet au menu.
    Le plus simple : garder projects/ comme page et ajouter un lien de menu.

Voici 3 méthodes fiables (choisis UNE) :

Méthode A — Fichier de navigation (Minimal Mistakes & co.)

  1. Crée (ou ouvre) /_data/navigation.yml

  2. Ajoute :

yaml
main:
  - title: "Portfolio"
    url: /portfolio/
  - title: "Projects"
    url: /projects/

  1. Commit + Push.

Si ton thème utilise navigation.yml, c’est la meilleure méthode.

Méthode B — header_pages (thèmes Jekyll par défaut)

Dans _config.yml, ajoute ou complète :

yaml
header_pages:
  - index.md
  - portfolio/index.md
  - projects/index.md

Ça force l’apparition des pages indiquées dans la barre de navigation.

Méthode C — Transformer en collection (option avancée)

Si tu tiens à la collection, fais ces 3 changements :

  1. Déplace/renomme projects/ → _projects/ (le underscore est obligatoire pour une collection).

  2. Mets ceci dans _config.yml :

yaml
collections:
  projects:
    output: true
    permalink: /projects/:name/

  1. Ajoute le lien au menu (avec Méthode A ou B), p.ex. :

yaml
header_pages:
  - portfolio/index.md
  - projects/index.md   # (tu peux créer une page sommaire /projects/index.md)

Important

  • Ton bloc actuel dans _config.yml :

    ruby
    Projects:
  output: true
  permalink: /:collection/:path/# _projects

    n’est pas au bon endroit (il doit être sous collections:) et Projects doit être en minuscule si tu l’utilises : projects:.
    Et comme tes fichiers sont dans projects/ (sans _), ça ne s’applique pas.

Ce que je te conseille maintenant (le plus simple)

# Risk Factors – ITN Guinea DHS 2018

> **Period:** 2021–2022  
> **Role:** Principal Investigator & Lead Data Analyst  
> **Location:** Guinea (national household survey)

## Overview
This project analyzed the 2018 Guinea Demographic and Health Survey (DHS) data to identify individual and household-level factors associated with insecticide-treated net (ITN) ownership and usage. The analysis provided evidence to refine national vector-control messaging and distribution strategies.

## Data
- Guinea DHS 2018 standard recode microdata.  
- Derived indicators for:
  - Household wealth quintiles
  - Education levels
  - Urban/rural residence
  - Household composition
- Dependent variables: ITN ownership, ITN use the night before the survey.

## Methods
- Complex survey analysis accounting for weights, clusters, and strata.
- Logistic regression models for ITN ownership and ITN use.
- Model diagnostics and adjusted odds ratios.
- Data cleaning and transformation in R.

## Tools
- **R packages:** `survey`, `srvyr`, `dplyr`, `broom`, `ggplot2`
- Data visualization for regression results and coverage maps.

## Deliverables
- Reproducible R scripts for survey data analysis.
- Tables and figures for manuscript and policy brief.
- Interpretation of results for non-technical audiences.

## Impact
- Provided the National Malaria Control Program with actionable insights on target groups for ITN campaigns.
- Informed tailored behavior change communication strategies.

## Suggested Repository Structure

Risk_factors_ITN_Guinea_DHS_2018/
├─ data/ # DHS data (not public) + derived variables
├─ R/ # Scripts for cleaning, analysis, plots
├─ outputs/ # Tables, figures
└─ README.md

# Risk Factors – ITN Guinea DHS 2018

> **Period:** 2021–2022  
> **Role:** Principal Investigator & Lead Data Analyst  
> **Location:** Guinea (national household survey)

## Overview
This project analyzed the 2018 Guinea Demographic and Health Survey (DHS) data to identify individual and household-level factors associated with insecticide-treated net (ITN) ownership and usage. The findings provided actionable insights to refine national vector-control messaging and distribution strategies.

## Data
- Guinea DHS 2018 standard recode microdata.
- Derived indicators for:
  - Household wealth quintiles
  - Education levels
  - Urban/rural residence
  - Household composition
- Dependent variables: ITN ownership, ITN use the night before the survey.

## Methods
- Complex survey analysis accounting for weights, clusters, and strata.
- Logistic regression models for ITN ownership and ITN use.
- Model diagnostics and adjusted odds ratios.
- Data cleaning and transformation in R.

## Tools
- **R packages:** `survey`, `srvyr`, `dplyr`, `broom`, `ggplot2`
- Data visualization for regression results and coverage maps.

## Deliverables
- Reproducible R scripts for survey data analysis.
- Tables and figures for manuscript and policy brief.
- Interpretation of results for non-technical audiences.

## Impact
- Provided the National Malaria Control Program with evidence to target high-priority groups in ITN campaigns.
- Informed tailored behavior change communication strategies.

**"Factors associated with the use of insecticide-treated nets in Guinea: an analysis of the 2018 Demographic and Health Survey"**.  
The objective was to identify household and individual-level determinants of ITN ownership and use, in order to inform national malaria prevention strategies.

---

## Data
- **Source:** Guinea DHS 2018 (Demographic and Health Survey)  
- **Access:** Available from the [DHS Program](https://dhsprogram.com/data/available-datasets.cfm) upon request  
- **Key variables:** Household wealth quintiles, education, residence type, household composition, ITN ownership, ITN use

---

## Methods
- Complex survey analysis accounting for weights, clusters, and strata
- Logistic regression for ITN ownership and ITN use among those with access
- Bivariate, univariate, and multivariate models
- Analysis performed in **R**

---

## Repository Structure

Indicators/ # Scripts for calculating household and individual-level indicators
Household_and_individual_level_indicators.R
Recoding of variables in the PR file.R

Risk_factors_Analysis/ # Scripts for bivariate, univariate, and multivariate analysis
Househod_ITN_ownership_risk_factors.R
ITN_use_among_with_access_risk_factors.R

yaml

---

## How to Use
1. Run `Household_and_individual_level_indicators.R` in the `Indicators/` directory to recode the selected variables at the household level and calculate the indicators.
2. Execute `Recoding of variables in the PR file.R` script.
3. Run `Househod_ITN_ownership_risk_factors.R` in the `Risk_factors_Analysis/` folder to estimate risk factors for ITN ownership.
4. Run `ITN_use_among_with_access_risk_factors.R` in the `Risk_factors_Analysis/` folder to estimate risk factors for ITN use among those with access.

---

## Impact
- Provided evidence to the National Malaria Control Program for targeted ITN distribution and behavior change communication strategies
- Supports academic research and programmatic decision-making on malaria prevention in Guinea

Analysis of the 2018 Guinea Demographic and Health Survey (DHS) to identify determinants of **ownership** and **use** of insecticide-treated nets (ITNs) at both household and individual levels. The goal was to inform the National Malaria Control Program’s distribution and communication strategies.

## Key Highlights
- Main variables: wealth quintiles, education level, urban/rural setting, household composition.
- Two main outcomes: **ITN ownership** and **ITN use the previous night** (among those with access).
- Accounted for complex survey design: weights, strata, and clusters.

## Methods & Tools
Survey-weighted logistic regression models were implemented using R (`survey`, `srvyr`, `dplyr`, `ggplot2`) to estimate adjusted odds ratios and visualize disparities.

## Deliverables
- Tables and figures for manuscript and policy brief.
- Fully reproducible R scripts (data cleaning, indicator generation, modeling).

## Impact
- Provided evidence to better target **priority groups** in ITN distribution campaigns.
- Informed recommendations for tailoring behavior change communication messages.

Voici une progression logique pour réviser les fondamentaux CDISC avant de coder :

🔹 1. Rappel CDISC et Standards

  • CDISC : organisation qui définit les standards de structuration et soumission des données cliniques.

  • Deux standards clés :

    • SDTM (Study Data Tabulation Model) → organisation des données brutes pour la soumission à la FDA.

    • ADaM (Analysis Data Model) → datasets dérivés utilisés pour les analyses statistiques.

  • But : assurer cohérence, traçabilité, et conformité aux exigences réglementaires (FDA/EMA).

🔹 2. SDTM – Concepts de base

  • Structure :

    • Un domaine = un sujet (DM = démographie, AE = adverse events, LB = labs, VS = vital signs…).

    • Toujours des variables standardisées : STUDYID, USUBJID, DOMAIN, --TESTCD, --ORRES, etc.

  • Clés :

    • DOMAIN = identifie le domaine (AE, DM…).

    • USUBJID = identifiant unique patient.

    • VISITNUM/VISITDY = temps.

  • SUPPQUAL : fichier SUPP-- pour stocker des variables additionnelles non standard.

🔹 3. ADaM – Concepts de base

  • ADSL = Analysis Dataset Subject-Level → dataset pivot avec toutes les infos sujet (traitement, population, randomisation).

  • ADaM BDS = Basic Data Structure → pour des analyses de mesures répétées (ex: efficacité, labs).

  • Variables clés :

    • PARAM/PARAMCD = paramètre étudié.

    • AVAL = valeur numérique analysée.

    • AVISIT/AVISITN = visite d’analyse.

    • TRTP/TRTPN = traitement.

  • Règles CDISC ADaM : traçabilité claire vers SDTM, ready-for-analysis.

🔹 4. Mapping SDTM → ADaM

Exemple classique :

  • SDTM LB (Laboratory) → ADaM ADLB (Laboratory Analysis).

  • Variables issues de SDTM (LBORRES, LBNRIND) sont transformées en AVAL, BASE, CHG, etc.

  • ADSL est construit principalement à partir de DM, EX, DS, SV (démographie, exposition, discontinuation, visits).

🔹 5. Ce qu’il faut maîtriser en priorité

✅ Différence SDTM vs ADaM
✅ Variables obligatoires dans DM et ADSL
✅ Structure d’un dataset BDS (ex: ADAE, ADLB)
✅ Règles de traçabilité (comment un AVAL d’ADaM vient d’une variable SDTM)

# Clinical Trials Programming Portfolio (CDISC Standards)

This portfolio project simulates a **clinical trial programming workflow** following CDISC standards (SDTM, ADaM) and the generation of submission-ready deliverables (TLFs, define.xml, QC).  
It demonstrates my ability to implement a **full pipeline** from raw clinical data to regulatory submission deliverables using **SAS**.

---

## 📂 Project Structure

- **SDTM/**  
  Programs for mapping raw data into SDTM domains (DM, AE, VS, SUPPDM).  
  Includes derivations and metadata checks.

- **ADAM/**  
  Programs to derive ADaM datasets (ADSL, ADAE).  
  Includes baseline flags, change-from-baseline, and treatment group derivations.

- **Analysis_datasets/**  
  Analysis-ready datasets for efficacy and safety endpoints.  
  Linked directly to TLF generation.

- **01_TLF_Deliverables/**  
  Example outputs for Tables, Listings, and Figures:  
  - Adverse Events summary table  
  - Patient disposition listing  
  - Kaplan–Meier survival curve  

- **macros/**  
  Reusable SAS macros for automation (e.g., QC comparisons, table summaries).

- **validation/**  
  QC programs to cross-check primary deliverables (ADSL vs QC ADSL, TLF double programming).

- **define.xml/**  
  Mock define.xml file to document metadata and dataset structures.

---

## 🚀 Key Skills Demonstrated
- Implementation of **CDISC standards** (SDTM, ADaM).  
- Creation of **ADSL and ADAE datasets**.  
- Development of **TLFs** (Tables, Listings, Figures).  
- Writing and using **SAS macros** for efficiency.  
- Performing **QC/validation** with double programming.  
- Documenting metadata with **define.xml**.

---

## 🔗 How to Use
1. Navigate to each folder and run the SAS programs in sequence:  
   - `SDTM` → `ADAM` → `Analysis_datasets` → `01_TLF_Deliverables`.  
2. Review outputs in `01_TLF_Deliverables/` for final deliverables.  
3. Check `validation/` for QC results.

This project is **based on simulated data and examples** inspired by clinical programming references (training materials, textbooks).

This project explores determinants of ITN (insecticide-treated net) ownership in Guinea (DHS 2018).
